{"title_page": "Erwin James", "text_new": "'''Erwin James Monahan''' (born 1957) is a convicted [[murderer]] and has been a contributor and columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' since 1998, writing under the name \"Erwin James\". He was released in August 2004 having served 20 years of a life sentence.<ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,3604,1010880,00.html\n|title=The inside story\n|first= Ian\n|last=Mayes\n|work=[[The Guardian]]\n|date=2003-08-02\n|accessdate=2008-03-17\n| location=London\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/erwin_james/profile.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | date=2 October 2007 | accessdate=2 May 2010 | first=Erwin | last=James | title=Erwin James}}</ref> From 2000 he wrote a regular column about prison life entitled ''A Life Inside''. It was the first column of its kind in the history of British journalism. He has continued to write for the national press and is the editor-in-chief of ''Inside Time'', a national newspaper in the UK for people in prison, as well as doing charity work, since his release. While he was in prison he did not receive fees for his articles; instead these were paid to a charity, the [[Prisoners' Advice Service]], which had helped him.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/may/19/books.guardianreview4 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ian | last=Mayes | title=Inside story | date=19 May 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMonahan's mother died in a car crash when he was seven, he was separated from his sister when she was twenty months old. Following the crash his grieving father turned to alcohol and became a violent drunk, inflicting much of his angst on his subsequent partners and on the young Erwin. Monahan committed his first crime when he was ten, breaking into a sweet shop. He eventually notched up 53 criminal convictions, including for burglary, theft, criminal damage, assault and mugging and including the final two for murder for which he was sentenced to Life.\n\nMonahan and his co-defendant, William Ross, whom he had met in a squat in London, were convicted of murdering theatrical agent Greville Hallam and [[solicitor]] Angus Cochran in 1982. Hallam was found [[strangled]] in his home in [[London]]. Cochran was murdered three months later after being [[mugged]]. Following the murders Monahan fled to France and joined the [[French Foreign Legion]], serving in [[Corsica]] and Africa. After receiving information from Ross, Monahan was traced by [[Scotland Yard]], and in August 1984 he handed himself in to the British Consul in [[Nice]].\n\nMonahan and Ross both pleaded not guilty to murder on both charges, each blaming the other for the killings. Another man implicated in the murders, Paul Dunwell, avoided prosecution by agreeing to give evidence for the prosecution against the pair. Justice Otton, who presided over the case, described Monahan as \"brutal, vicious and callous\" and sentenced him to [[life imprisonment]] with a minimum term of 14 years, subsequently increased to 25 years by the [[Home Secretary]].<ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2009/apr/24/erwin-james-monahan-guardian\n|title=The Guardian and Erwin James\n|first= Ian\n|last= Katz\n|work=[[The Guardian]]\n|date=2009-04-24\n|accessdate=2010-09-10\n| location=London\n}}</ref>\nRoss was also sentenced to life imprisonment; he was released from prison to a hostel in March 2014.\n\nIn January 2006, Monahan wrote an article for ''G2'',  a section of ''The Guardian'' (as \"Erwin James\", as always), recalling his time in the French Foreign Legion.<ref>Erwin James, \"Legion of Honour\", ''The Guardian'', 13 January 2006</ref> In 2009 he admitted that part of the article contained information detailing experiences in [[Beirut]] which were untrue, as he had not, in fact, served there.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Guardian |date=27 April 2009 |title=Open door: The readers' editor on... truth and fiction in a writer's life story}}</ref>\n\nFor the majority of the time during which he wrote for ''The Guardian'' the circumstances leading to his arrests and convictions were not revealed, but in April 2009 Monahan's full name became public.<ref name=realme>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2009/apr/24/erwin-james-journalism \"The Real Me\"], Erwin James, ''The Guardian'', Friday 24 April 2009</ref>\n\nMonahan wrote in ''G2'' in April 2009 that his behaviour had been unforgivable and that \"I seek no forgiveness now.\"<ref name=realme />\n\n==Published works==\n*''A Life Inside: A Prisoner's Notebook'' (2003)\n*''The Home Stretch: From Prison to Parole''  (2005)\n*''Redeemable: A Memoir of Darkness and Hope'' (2016)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Erwin}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:Soldiers of the French Foreign Legion]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:English prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n", "text_old": "'''Erwin James Monahan''' (born 1957) is a convicted [[murderer]] and has been a contributor and columnist for ''[[The Guardian]]'' since 1998, writing under the name \"Erwin James\". He was released in August 2004 having served 20 years of a life sentence.<ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,3604,1010880,00.html\n|title=The inside story\n|first= Ian\n|last=Mayes\n|work=[[The Guardian]]\n|date=2003-08-02\n|accessdate=2008-03-17\n| location=London\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/erwin_james/profile.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | date=2 October 2007 | accessdate=2 May 2010